s is led by the interventions of Indigenous artists, including Robert Houle, Nadia Myre, Cheryl L’Hirondelle, and Rebecca Belmore. Bringing together media theories of documentation and the strategies of these artists, Settler Colonial Ways of Seeing develops a method for identifying how bureaucratic documents mediate power relations as well as how those relations may be disobeyed and re-imagined.By integrating art-led inquiry with media theory and settler colonial studies approaches, Taschereau Mamers offers a political and media history of the documents that have reproduced Indian status. More importantly, she provides us with an innovative guide for using art as a method of theorizing decolonial political relations. This is a crucial book for any reader interested in the intersection of state archives, settler colonial studies, and visual culture in the context of Canada’s complex and violent relationship with Indigenous peoples.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aColonizationxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aEthnology in art. 0aEthnosociologyzCanada. 0aIndigenous artxPolitical aspects. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxSociological aspects. 0aLegal documentszCanadaxIdentification. 4aArt & Visual Culture. 4aCommunications. 4aNative & Indigenous Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh  aArt.  aCanada.  aIndigenous art.  aIndigenous politics.  aMedia history.  aMedia studies.  aMedia theory.  aPolitical theory.  aVisual art.  abureaucracy.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781531505226?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781531505226423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781531505226/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles